Charles Stewart who days previously had been defeated at Worcester. In the superb portrait of Cromwell we see a self-torturing despot who attempts to be in full control in the name of religion; in the rakish Charles we see a man without self-reflection whose own libertarianism after his restoration to the English throne in 1660 permitted a great burgeoning in scientific enquiry and the arts.This edition of Woodstock is based on the first, but emended in the light of readings in the manuscript and proofs that were misread, and at times deliberately suppressed, as Scott's own handwritten words were turned into a printed book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, J. H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aInglis, Tony, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLumsden, Alison, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074860583540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074862830840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748628308423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748628308/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK